Message-ID: <CAFDcVCQxSUnRPkNBmZr2Fcm6Fho_-m-7dNYYMhsg2nvh+tYUeA@mail.gmail.com>

Kasper, correct me if I'm wrong...

The way I understand it, Kasper would like a way to test on an
*identical* setup such that he can reproduce the issues he sees on the
Bioc servers, but that he cannot reproduce elsewhere.  I've been there
a few times as well and when it happens you end up spending lots of
hours only trying to reverse engineering the exact setup on the test
servers so you can actually fix the problem.  Going down this path is
uncertain, because you never know how much time you have to spend on
this.  The alternative is to commit what you think is a fix and then
wait and see for those 24-36 hours Kasper is talking about, and in
worst case, repeat over and over.

For these hard-to-troubleshoot problems, I'd say you pretty much need
access to the actual test machines.  It's possible that VM images
would be an option, but I doubt OS X/Windows images are allowed to be
distributed (...or even run; yes, I'm talking about you A...).  The
other option would be to have a Bioc service like
http://win-builder.r-project.org/.  To prevent swamping the main
build/check, the service could be limited to bioc package maintainers,
and possibly also a quota per day/week.

/Henrik



